  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, think Down Syndrome and double bubble!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Duodenal atresia. This diagnosis is strongly suggested by the clinical presentation of projectile vomiting soon after birth in an infant with features suggestive of Down Syndrome (single palmar crease, epicanthic folds) and a soft, non-distended abdomen.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDuodenal atresia is a congenital obstruction of the duodenum, often occurring at or distal to the ampulla of Vater. Its strong association with Trisomy 21 (Down Syndrome) is a key diagnostic clue. The high level of obstruction prevents gas and fluid from passing distally, leading to a non-distended abdomen. Vomiting typically occurs within the first 24-48 hours of life, often projectile, and can be bilious if the obstruction is distal to the ampulla. The absence of abdominal distension differentiates it from lower intestinal obstructions.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Pyloric stenosis) (Incorrect): Pyloric stenosis typically presents at 3-6 weeks of age, not immediately after birth, and is not associated with Down Syndrome.\nOption C (Milk allergy) (Incorrect): Milk allergy presents later in infancy, usually weeks to months after birth, with symptoms like diarrhea, blood in stool, and fussiness, not acute projectile vomiting soon after birth.\nOption D (Meconium ileus) (Incorrect): Meconium ileus is a distal small bowel obstruction, typically presenting with abdominal distension, failure to pass meconium, and bilious vomiting. It is strongly associated with Cystic Fibrosis, not Down Syndrome, and the abdomen would be distended.\nOption E (Anal atresia) (Incorrect): Anal atresia presents with failure to pass meconium and progressive abdominal distension. Vomiting would be a later symptom and the abdomen would be distended, not soft and non-distended.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature             | Duodenal Atresia                               | Pyloric Stenosis                               | Meconium Ileus                               |\n|---------------------|------------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------------|\n| Onset               | First 24-48 hours of life                      | 3-6 weeks of age                               | First 24-48 hours of life                    |\n| Vomiting            | Projectile, often bilious, soon after feeding  | Projectile, non-bilious                        | Bilious, progressive                         |\n| Abdomen             | Soft, non-distended                            | Non-distended                                  | Distended                                    |\n| Associated Syndromes| Down Syndrome (Trisomy 21)                     | None                                           | Cystic Fibrosis                              |\n| Imaging             | \"Double Bubble\" sign on X-ray                  | \"String sign\" on UGI, \"Olive\" on ultrasound    | Ground glass appearance, microcolon on enema |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Down Syndrome + early projectile vomiting + non-distended abdomen = Duodenal Atresia.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain abdominal X-ray, the classic finding for duodenal atresia is the 'double bubble' sign, representing air in the stomach and the proximal dilated duodenum, separated by the pylorus. There would be no distal gas.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Infants with Down Syndrome (2022): Recommends screening for duodenal atresia in all infants with Down Syndrome.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pyloric stenosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Duodenal atresia | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Milk allergy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Meconium ileus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Anal atresia | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Pediatric Surgical Emergencies MCQ.pdf**\n",
