  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When it's ileo-ileal, go for the steel!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, undertake a laparotomy. For an ileo-ileal intussusception, non-operative reduction techniques like hydrostatic or pneumatic enemas are generally ineffective and carry a higher risk of perforation, making surgical intervention the safest and most definitive approach.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIleo-ileal intussusception, especially in a 14-month-old, often has a pathological lead point (e.g., Meckel's diverticulum, polyp, lymphoma) that prevents successful non-operative reduction. Laparotomy allows for direct visualization of the intussusception, manual reduction, identification and removal of any lead point, and resection of non-viable bowel if reduction is unsuccessful or complications exist. This direct surgical approach minimizes the risk of missed pathology or complications associated with failed non-operative attempts.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Hydrostatic reduction with barium enema is primarily indicated for ileocolic intussusception, not ileo-ileal, and is less likely to be successful or safe in this specific type.\nOption B (Incorrect): Pneumatic reduction with air insufflation, like hydrostatic reduction, is mainly for ileocolic intussusception and carries a higher risk of perforation for ileo-ileal types.\nOption D (Incorrect): Colonoscopy is a diagnostic and therapeutic tool for the large bowel and cannot effectively reduce an ileo-ileal intussusception.\nOption E (Incorrect): Flexible sigmoidoscopy has an even more limited reach than colonoscopy and is entirely inappropriate for an ileo-ileal intussusception.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Ileocolic Intussusception | Ileo-ileal Intussusception |\n| :------------------ | :------------------------------------------------------ | :----------------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Prevalence** | Most common type (90-95%) | Less common (5-10%) |\n| **Lead Point** | Often idiopathic (viral illness) | More frequently associated with a pathological lead point |\n| **Presentation** | Classic triad: colicky pain, vomiting, \"currant jelly\" stool | Similar, but \"currant jelly\" stool less common; often more subtle |\n| **Initial Mgmt.** | Non-operative reduction (air/hydrostatic enema) | Surgical exploration (laparotomy) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Ileo-ileal intussusception usually requires surgery; non-operative reduction is for ileocolic.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a \"target sign\" or \"pseudokidney sign\" indicates intussusception. Intraoperatively, telescoping of the ileum into another segment of ileum will be visible.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nCurrent consensus in pediatric surgery recommends surgical exploration for ileo-ileal intussusception due to higher likelihood of pathological lead points and lower success rates with non-operative reduction.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Attempt hydrostatic reduction with barium enema | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Attempt pneumatic reduction with air insufflation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Undertake a laparotomy | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Undertake a colonoscopy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Undertake a flexible sigmoidoscopy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Pediatric Surgical Emergencies MCQ.pdf**\n",
