  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When a baby's stomach turns into a cannon, think pyloric stenosis!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question accurately describes the classic presentation of infantile hypertrophic pyloric stenosis. The combination of a 4-week-old infant, profuse and projectile non-bilious vomiting after feeds, and weight loss is pathognomonic for this condition.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nInfantile hypertrophic pyloric stenosis (IHPS) is characterized by hypertrophy and hyperplasia of the muscular layers of the pylorus, leading to gastric outlet obstruction. This obstruction prevents gastric contents from passing into the duodenum, causing the stomach to distend and forcefully eject its contents, resulting in projectile vomiting. The vomiting is non-bilious because the obstruction is proximal to the ampulla of Vater. The typical age of presentation is between 2 and 8 weeks of life, with a peak incidence around 4-6 weeks, fitting the patient's age perfectly. Persistent vomiting leads to dehydration, electrolyte imbalances (hypochloremic, hypokalemic metabolic alkalosis), and failure to thrive or weight loss.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Duodenal atresia typically presents earlier, often in the first few days of life, and usually causes bilious vomiting if distal to the ampulla of Vater. While it can be non-bilious if proximal, the vomiting is not typically described as projectile in the same manner as pyloric stenosis.\nOption B (Incorrect): Ileal atresia is a more distal obstruction, presenting with abdominal distension, bilious vomiting, and failure to pass meconium, not projectile non-bilious vomiting.\nOption D (Incorrect): Achalasia cardia is extremely rare in infants and presents with dysphagia, regurgitation, and failure to thrive, not typically projectile vomiting.\nOption E (Incorrect): Intestinal malrotation with midgut volvulus usually presents with bilious vomiting due to small bowel obstruction and ischemia. While it can present in infancy, non-bilious projectile vomiting is not its classic presentation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature             | Pyloric Stenosis                               | Duodenal Atresia                               | Intestinal Malrotation (with Volvulus)         |\n|---------------------|------------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------|------------------------------------------------|\n| **Age of Onset**    | 2-8 weeks (peak 4-6 weeks)                     | First 24-48 hours of life                      | First month of life, but can be later          |\n| **Vomiting Type**   | Projectile, non-bilious                        | Bilious (usually), non-bilious (if pre-ampullary) | Bilious (classic), can be non-bilious initially |\n| **Associated Signs**| Palpable 'olive' mass, visible peristalsis, weight loss, metabolic alkalosis | 'Double bubble' sign on X-ray, polyhydramnios (antenatal) | Abdominal distension, tenderness, bloody stools, shock |\n| **Pathology**       | Hypertrophy of pyloric muscle                  | Failure of duodenal lumen recanalization       | Abnormal rotation of midgut during development |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Projectile non-bilious vomiting in a 4-week-old infant is pyloric stenosis until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, the diagnostic criteria for pyloric stenosis include a pyloric muscle thickness of >3-4 mm and a pyloric channel length of >14-17 mm. Intraoperatively, the surgeon will observe a markedly thickened, firm, and elongated pylorus, often described as an 'olive-shaped' mass, which is incised longitudinally down to the submucosa (Ramstedt pyloromyotomy).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Hypertrophic Pyloric Stenosis (2018): Recommends ultrasound as the primary diagnostic imaging modality and surgical pyloromyotomy as the definitive treatment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Duodenal atresia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Ileal atresia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hypertrophy of the pyloric sphincter | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Achalasia cardia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Intestinal malrotation | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: UNKNOWN) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Pediatric Surgical Emergencies MCQ.pdf**\n",
