  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't operate on adenitis; it's a self-limiting imitator!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Mesenteric Adenitis. This diagnosis is highly suggested in a 7-year-old boy with right iliac fossa pain and fever, but with a soft abdomen and only mild tenderness, which is less typical for acute appendicitis after three days.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMesenteric adenitis is an inflammatory condition of the mesenteric lymph nodes, often triggered by a viral infection (e.g., adenovirus) or bacterial infection (e.g., Yersinia enterocolitica). The inflamed lymph nodes, typically in the ileocecal region, mimic appendicitis due to their proximity to the appendix. However, the tenderness is usually less localized and less severe than in appendicitis, and rebound tenderness or guarding are often absent, as seen in this patient's 'soft' abdomen.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Appendicitis would typically present with more localized and severe tenderness, often with guarding or rebound tenderness, especially after three days. While fever is present, the mild abdominal findings make it less likely.\nOption B (Incorrect): Crohn's disease is a chronic inflammatory bowel condition, not an acute presentation with high fever and mild, localized tenderness. It usually involves more systemic symptoms and chronic GI issues.\nOption D (Incorrect): Irritable bowel syndrome is a functional gastrointestinal disorder characterized by chronic abdominal pain and altered bowel habits, without fever or acute inflammatory signs.\nOption E (Incorrect): Threadworm infection (Enterobiasis) primarily causes perianal itching, especially at night. While abdominal pain can occur, it's not typically associated with acute, high-grade fever and localized RIF tenderness mimicking appendicitis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature             | Mesenteric Adenitis                               | Acute Appendicitis                                |\n| :------------------ | :------------------------------------------------ | :------------------------------------------------ |\n| **Age**             | Common in young children (5-15 years)             | Any age, peak in teens/20s                          |\n| **Pain Onset**      | Often gradual, may follow viral prodrome         | Periumbilical migrating to RIF, often acute       |\n| **Tenderness**      | RIF, often diffuse or less localized, mild        | Localized RIF (McBurney's), severe, guarding/rebound |\n| **Fever**           | Common, can be high                               | Common, usually lower grade initially             |\n| **WBC Count**       | Mildly elevated or normal                         | Usually elevated, neutrophilia                    |\n| **Imaging (US/CT)** | Enlarged mesenteric lymph nodes, normal appendix | Enlarged, non-compressible appendix, periappendiceal fat stranding |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: RIF pain + fever + soft abdomen in a child = think mesenteric adenitis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound or CT, mesenteric adenitis typically shows enlarged mesenteric lymph nodes (often >5mm in short axis) in the right lower quadrant, with a normal-appearing appendix. Intraoperatively, one would find enlarged, inflamed lymph nodes in the mesentery, particularly around the ileocecal region, but a healthy appendix.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Diagnosis and Management of Acute Appendicitis in Children (2010, reaffirmed 2014) recommends imaging (ultrasound or CT) to differentiate appendicitis from other causes of RIF pain.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Appendicitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Crohns disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Mesenteric adenitis | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Irritable bowel syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Threadworm infection | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Pediatric Surgical Emergencies MCQ.pdf**\n",
